Wrapper Classes in Java

Wrapper classes are those classes, which are used to 'wrap' primitive variables in such a way, that they behave like an object. 

1. byte - Byte (for wrapping byte value)
2. double - Double (for wrapping double value)
3. float - Float (for wrapping float value)
4. int - Integer (for wrapping int value)
5. long - Long (for wrapping long value)
6. short - Short (for wrapping short value)
7. char - Character (for wrapping char value)
8. boolean - Boolean (for wrapping boolean value)

All these wrapper class have parent class i.e. Number class

A) Autoboxing: 
1. Autoboxing is basically a technique in which compiler automatically wrap and unwrap the primitives in order to store them in 'ARRAYLIST'

B) Wrapping and un-wrapping a integer variable:
e.g. public class Test
     {
     public static void main(String[] args)
     {
     int i = 45;
     Integer wrapper = new Integer(i);
     System.out.println(wrapper);
     int unwrapped = wrapper.intValue();
     System.out.println(unwrapped);
     }
     } 